When she won her Oscar in 2018, Frances McDormand perfectly captured the ze=
itgeist with an acceptance speech that concluded, =E2=80=9CI have two words=
 to leave with you tonight, ladies and gentlemen: inclusion rider.=E2=80=9D=
 Back then, of course, Hollywood was the epicenter of resistance: to Donald=
 Trump, to sexual harassment, to the lack of race and gender diversity in e=
ntertainment. Hashtags like #MeToo and #OscarsSoWhite were buzzing on Twitt=
er, a platform Elon Musk had not yet colonized. McDormand=E2=80=99s proclam=
ation seemed to crystallize the beginning of a new, hopeful commitment to d=
iversity, equity, and inclusion. Today, as Trump prepares to return to offi=
ce, I wonder what would happen if an actress repeated those words so public=
ly.

McDormand=E2=80=99s cri de coeur came to mind over the weekend, after Trump=
 nominated
former California G.O.P. vice chair Harmeet Dhillon to head the Justice Dep=
artment=E2=80=99s civil rights division. Dhillon isn=E2=80=99t exactly Holl=
ywood=E2=80=99s version of a justice warrior. While Silicon Valley was goin=
g through its own #MeToo reckoning in 2017, Dhillon=E2=80=94who for years h=
as made a habit of filing lawsuits related to hot-button culture war issues=
=E2=80=94represented James Damore, the Google engineer who was fired after =
circulating a 10-page manifesto that critiqued the company=E2=80=99s divers=
ity initiatives and suggested that men might be more suited to certain role=
s in tech. The class-action suit that followed=E2=80=94alleging discriminat=
ion against white male conservatives at Google=E2=80=94was mocked but gaine=
d traction in court and ultimately resulted in a settlement, paving the way=
 for actress Gina Carano=E2=80=99s Musk-funded suit against Disney. Dhillon=
 became a fixture on Fox News, where she inevitably caught Trump=E2=80=99s =
eye.

