w they spend time and money. That=E2=80=99s product design, not expression,=
 they assert, and the First Amendment doesn=E2=80=99t protect <i>that</i>.<=
br/><br/>About a week ago, the video game companies responded, arguing that=
 the supposed distinction between =E2=80=9Ccontent=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cno=
n-expressive defective features=E2=80=9D is false, has never been drawn by
any court, and would have broad implications across media. They draw parall=
els to literary and musical techniques designed to engage audiences, such a=
s chapter-ending cliffhangers and catchy song choruses, noting that there=
=E2=80=99s no duty to warn about these either. <br/><br/>While the debate o=
ver KOSA has been muted so far, those paying attention see the video game a=
ddiction case as a harbinger. As the legal environment currently stands, Ac=
tivision and Epic <i>should</i> be deemed heavy favorites=E2=80=94however, =
if KOSA passes and imposes explicit duties of care regarding the more manip=
ulative elements of media, we may see a surge in similar lawsuits. Courts w=
